passages.text: Asia Pacific Equity Research 29 August 2025
FY25 result conference

We would like to flag our Reporting Season Spotlight series at 2.30pm, discussing the most topical result each day of reporting season. Today we will be discussing the NXT FY25 Result. Please register here.

If you are subject to the MiFID II Research Unbundling regime, you may only be eligible to participate in this event if you have the appropriate level of access to J.P. Morgan research. Please check your eligibility before participating/accessing. If you are unsure as to your eligibility, please reach out to your usual J.P. Morgan contact.
NXT.AX,NXT AU Price (28 Aug 25):A\(14.05 Price Target (Jun- 26):A\)16.50
Australia Technology, Media & Telecommunications

- FY27 is likely to see consensus upgrades. NXT highlighted a pull-forward in deployment of its forward order book with 57MW now expected to be deployed by the end of FY26 and 58MW in FY27. These contracts would grow NXT's revenue to \(\sim\) 700m at a 50% EBITDA margin in FY27, implying \(350m of EBITDA vs consensus of\) 309m. Any incremental contract wins from here will further support growth into FY28+.

- Optimistic around FY26 being another record year for 50-100MW contracts. On the call, mgmt was upbeat on the opportunity in FY26, which is set to potentially be another record year, with 50-100MW of contracts likely.

- Confident in getting approval for S5. NXT remains of the view that it will get the development approval to go ahead with S5, which has been under much scrutiny following rezoning changes in Macquarie Park. The company expects an announcement by the end of the year, and if approved would likely be a positive catalyst for the company.

- Seeking JV capital partner for S4/S7. NXT has hired advisors to set up a JV structure for its hyperscale developments at S4 and S7. S4 and S7 would represent at least 850MW of wholesale data center capacity and likely require \(\sim\) 515bn of funding. NXT is likely to tip in its existing land bank for these sites, and take a minority stake in a JV. NXT will also charge an asset management fee as the operator of the facilities. This de-risks the need for a capital raise for these facilities and allows NXT to more efficiently allocate its capital. NXT also expects a geared return of mid-teens ROE.

- Full-funded for existing sites, with capital raise only on acceleration of the pipeline. Following the debt upsize earlier in the month, NXT has \(5.5bn of liquidity available to be deployed. Importantly, the company reiterated that the banks look at interest coverage on a contracted order book basis, which does make spot metrics on leverage less relevant. The company feels very comfortable that its balance sheet and liquidity headroom is sufficient to fund current projects.
- Japan JV secured with CBRE IM for 30MW site to go live in FY30. NXT

has marked another significant milestone in its regional expansion plans by securing a partner for its first Tokyo site. Initial capex outlay over FY26/FY27 is likely to be low, before ramping up ahead of the targeted go live in FY30.

- No erosion of pricing for wholesale deals. NXT remains very comfortable with an assumption of \(\sim \$ 2m\) net revenue/MW for wholesale/hyperscale deals and noted no compression in pricing on the back of the demand/supply imbalance driven by the major hyperscalers, as well as emerging neo-cloud and AI companies.
NextDC (Overweight; Price Target: A\(16.50)

With data centers in the five major capital cities, NextDC is one of the leading data- center operators in Australia and the only pure play on the Australian data- center market. With its first- generation data centers in Brisbane, Sydney and Melbourne completely sold out, and similar progress with its generation two facilities, the company is rapidly scaling up by building larger and more dense facilities. We expect these facilities to generate a mid- to high- teens IRR as they fill and benefit from the strong demand from both hyperscalers and enterprise customers. We do see strong competition from incumbents, but note that NXT's differentiated model and broader presence across Australia are likely to present a point of difference.

Our Jun- 26 price target of A\(16.50 is based on a discounted cash flow that assumes a 7.4% WACC and a 3.5% perpetual growth rate. We derive our WACC estimate based on the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), which assumes a 10- year risk- free rate of 4.0%, equity risk premium of 5.0%, beta of 1.00, D/D+E ratio of 35%, and tax rate of 30%.

- Constrained supply, driven by construction risks.

- As with NXT's S2 facility, we saw significant construction delays due to the complexity of building large and vertical data centres. Any construction delays could lead to a lack of available capacity to sell through.
Upside catalysts include:

- NextDC operates best-in-class facilities in the industry with high barriers to entry.- NextDC is the first data center operator in the world to achieve Tier IV certification by The Uptime Institute on its second-generation data centers without having a full 2N+1 redundancy system. This allows NextDC not only to attract customers that require best-in-class data center facilities, but also to operate with a lower fixed-cost base than competitors.- Continued exponential growth in data and cloud computing remains a secular tailwind for data centers.- While NextDC has been able to ride the remarkable 20%+ CAGR of cloud computing, IT outsourcing and data usage growth over the last five years, we do not expect exponential growth to slow anytime soon. Cisco estimates high-teens growth in cloud computing globally, while Internet traffic and data usage continue to grow at 20%+ annually.- We estimate a mid-to-high-teens IRR on second-generation data centers.- NextDC has achieved a low- to mid-20% IRR on its first-generation data centers in Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane. With capacity selling out within five to seven years and continued growth in Interconnectivity revenues, the company has proven its expertise in building out top-tier data centers and is able to attract a strong ecosystem of telecom vendors and partners. We estimate that the second-generation data centers will achieve mid- to high-teens returns despite being many times larger. These are favourable returns compared to its WACC of 9.4%.- Global expansion by large data center operators could drive industry M&A.- As the recent acquisitions of Metronode by Equinix, Ascenty by Digital Realty, Zenium by CyrusOne and CyrusOne’s strategic partnership with GDS Holdings show, US-based data center operators are looking to expand internationally in order to meet customer demand. With long lead times for construction and difficulty securing prime real estate in metros, it makes more sense for these operators to acquire data centers than to build them themselves, in our view. This is particularly true if the data centers are recently built and are up to the highest standards, like those of NextDC.
